<!--Updating your starter file-->
<h3 id="update-your-starter-file">Update Your Starter File</h3>
<p>
    Use these steps to make sure your <strong>FishTales</strong> starter file includes all report sites and their relevant details. This helps FishTales scrape and summarize reports accurately.
</p>
<ol>
    <li>
        Run <strong>SiteScout</strong> to check if your starter file is missing any report sites.
    </li>
    <li>
        For each new URL found, open the website in your browser.
    </li>
    <li>
        Identify where the site publishes its reports (this could be a news section, blog, or updates page).
    </li>
    <li>
        Take note of any <strong>keywords</strong>, <strong>junk-words</strong>, or ‚Äúclick here‚Äù type links that indicate new content (sometimes called click-phrases). Record each in the <strong>respective column</strong> of your starter file.
    </li>
    <li>
        Inspect the page to find the section containing the report:
        <ul>
            <li>Right-click on a report and choose <strong>Inspect</strong> (or <strong>Inspect Element</strong>).</li>
            <li>Keyboard shortcuts:
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Windows/Linux:</strong> <code>Ctrl + Shift + I</code> or <code>F12</code></li>
                    <li><strong>Mac:</strong> <code>Cmd + Option + I</code> or <code>F12</code></li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Look for the container that surrounds the report content. This could be an <code>&lt;article&gt;</code>, a <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> with a <code>post</code> class, or another identifiable element.</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        Record the appropriate CSS selector for that section in the ‚ÄúSelector‚Äù column of your starter file. This tells FishTales exactly where to pull report content from.
    </li>
    <li>
        The ‚ÄúLast Updated‚Äù column is for your reference only; it doesn‚Äôt affect how the tool works. You can use it to keep track of when you last checked a site.
    </li>
</ol>

<h5>Advanced Selectors</h5>
<p>
    Most of the time, you can find a simple CSS selector like <code>&lt;article&gt;</code> or a <code>div.post</code> to grab the report content. These are easier to use and less likely to break if the website changes.
</p>
<p>
    However, some websites don‚Äôt have clear containers for the reports. In those cases, you may need to use <strong>advanced selectors</strong> to be more specific. For example:
</p>
<pre><code>div.entry-content:has(p:text-matches("Fishing Report", "i"))</code></pre>
<p>
    This selector looks for a <code>div</code> with the class <code>entry-content</code> that contains a paragraph with text matching "Fishing Report" (case-insensitive). Using this approach can help you target the exact content you need without grabbing unrelated sections of the page.
</p>
<p>
    ‚ö†Ô∏è Advanced selectors can be tricky. They may not always work perfectly, especially if the website structure changes. If you‚Äôre unsure, it‚Äôs a good idea to use a chatbot like <strong>GPT</strong> or <strong>Gemini</strong> to help you craft the correct selector.
</p>
<p>
    Tips for using advanced selectors:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>Start simple and only use advanced features when necessary.</li>
    <li>Test your selector in the browser console before adding it to your starter file.</li>
    <li>Remember that overly complex selectors can break if the website layout changes.</li>
    <li>Document your selectors in the starter file so you can troubleshoot later if needed.</li>
</ul>
<p>
    By using advanced selectors carefully, you can ensure FishTales captures the exact report content even on tricky websites.
</p>

